ate and distinct from executive remuneration. The remuneration of NEDs for the years ended 30 June 2025 and 30 June 2024 are disclosed in Table 1 on page 52 of this report. 50 Annual Report 2025 Harvey Norman Holdings Limited (ACN 003 237 545) 10 Relationship between Remuneration and Performance The graphs below illustrate the performance of the consolidated entity for the past five financial years and the high level of correlation between remuneration and performance. Correlation is a calculation of the degree of relationship between two items with 100% being strongest and 0% being weakest. Correlation between the indicators of performance and remuneration remain strong. Reported PBT return on net assets (%) vs Correlation 5-YEAR: 77.2% Total remuneration expense* Total remuneration expense Reported PBT * For directors of the HNHL Board return on net assets YEAR ENDED 30 JUNE Total remuneration expense* and Total remuneration expense Correlation Total “At risk” remuneration remuneration “At risk” remuneration vs NPAT & NCI NPAT&NCI 5-YEAR: 74.3% 88.2% “At risk” remuneration YEAR ENDED 30 JUNE Average share price, earnings per share and Correlation Average share price Earning per share Dividends paid dividends paid per share vs “At risk” remuneration 5-YEAR: 28.3% 88.2% 93.9% Average Earnings per Dividends Paid per share price share share ‘At risk’ remuneration * For directors of the HNHL Board YEAR ENDED 30 JUNE Annual Report 2025 Harvey Norman Holdings Limited (ACN 003 237 545) 51 Directors’ Report Remuneration Report - Audited (continued) 11 Compensation of Key Management Personnel Table 1: Compensation of Key Management Personnel Expensed for the Year Ended 30 June 2025 Directors of Harvey Norman Holdings Limited: POST LONG TERM SHORT-TERM BENEFITS OTHER EMPLOYMENT INCENTIVES Non- Long % Salary & Performance Other Super- Performance Total Monetary Service earned Fees Cash Incentive Short Term (a) annuation Rights Remuneration In $AUD Benefits (a) Leave (b) at ri