Norman Holdings Limited (ACN 003 237 545) Sustainability Report This report outlines the position and progress of the Company and each relevant controlled entity on key sustainability matters. To prepare for mandatory climate-related disclosures under the Australian Sustainability Reporting Standards (ASRS) beginning in FY2026, the Company advanced its systems, processes, and governance practices. The European Union’s Corporate Sustainability Reporting Directive (CSRD), originally scheduled for FY2026, has been deferred. Entities within the Group are now expected to report under CSRD from FY2028. The Company continues to report on material sustainability issues under its established governance and compliance risk framework. Sustainability Governance The ESC meets regularly to review performance and reports to a Board committee on compliance matters. The Company’s core objective is to generate long-term sustainable value for shareholders. Directors consider the interests Sustainability Working Group of relevant community stakeholders when making decisions. The ESC formed a Sustainability Working Group (SWG) to support The Company and its controlled entities maintain and enhance readiness for mandatory reporting in Australia, the EU, and other a corporate governance and compliance framework to support jurisdictions. this objective and meet regulatory obligations (Sustainability Framework). Sustainability Policy Sustainability remains a strategic priority for the Board and The Company adopted a sustainability policy to guide management. The Board oversees the Sustainability Framework, strategic decision-making by integrating sustainability risks and including risk and compliance controls related to sustainability opportunities into business operations. commitments. The policy directs the Company and its controlled entities The Framework enables effective identification and management to generate long-term shareholder value while considering of sustainability risks and opportunities. stakeholder interests, aligned with the Company’s Statement of Values. A controlled entity established an Executive Sustainability Committee (ESC), comprising employees and three executive Three Pillars of Sustainability directors. The ESC develops, implements, and improves policies The Sustainability Framework guides activities across three and procedures to ensure compliance with sustainability strategic pillars: People, Places, and Products. obligations across business operations. People Diversity & Inclusion Each relevant controlled entity recognises and values the contribution of people from diverse backgrounds. Globally, each relevant member of the consolidated entity offers inclusive employment opportunities across a wide range of industries and roles. It maintains gender balance across employee and senior executive teams, with women holding 40% of senior executive positions globally. The consolidated entity continues to build a diverse leadership pipeline, advancing future leaders from within its existing talent pool. CEO Katie Page remains one of only 19 female CEOs in ASX200 companies. Annual Report 2025 Harvey Norman® Holdings Limited (ACN 003 237 545) 5599 Directors’ Report Sustainability Report (continued) A Global Pipeline of Women Leaders 50% Women of Manager Directors comprise of all global regions 40% Women of Senior Executives comprise across all global regions 45% Women of Employees across comprise all global regions The consolidated entity monitors gender representation across the During FY25, a relevant controlled entity undertook a number workforce, including its Board and executive teams, and upholds of initiatives aimed at educating and celebrating the range of its commitment to equal employment opportunity and pay equity. cultures, backgrounds, and abilities of our global workforce, and Each relevant controlled entity tracks and reports progress to aims to continue to strengthen this approach. ensure compliance with this commitment. Staff Engagement & Wellbeing Australia and Ireland publicly report annual Gender Pay Gap (GPG) data. In Australia, GPG data is submitted to the Workplace Gender Each relevant member of the consolidated entity recognises Equality Agency (WGEA) for ten controlled entities, covering that workforce engagement drives productivity, retention, and sectors such as manufacturing, logistics, retail, IT, property, and performance. In late FY25, the first global engagement survey administration. A copy of the WGEA report for the period 1 April was launched, enabling employees to provide feedback on their 2024 to 31 March 2025 is available on the website. These figures experience at work. These insights will inform people strategies exclude employees of independent Harvey Norman®, Domayne®, across the consolidated entity in FY26 and beyond. Teams
